commit_message: ... and here finally comes Predis!
Fixed and extended the README
Now I am done fixing README. Seriously.
Fixed a value in the shared configurations for the library examples
Fixed a leftover from a test. Oh well, this actually shows off how transparent can be switching from inline/bulk commands to multibulk commands.
Fixed a typo in the readme
Renamed a method of CommandPipeline to a more appropriate name
Initial support for optional parameters when creating a Client instance. Optional authorization and database selection are now performed automatically upon connection.
Introduced the new ConnectionParameters class
Refactored the pipeline bits. Now a pipeline buffer can be flushed from inside a pipeline block to free up the memory used by the commands stored in the buffer on the client.
Now the Connection class internally uses only the passed ConnectionParameters instance
Fixed a small oversight
Minor optimization in the HashRing class when adding/removing nodes from the ring
Customizable number of replicas when creating an instance of HashRing
Increased the default number of replicas for HashRing
Fixed a bug in HashRing::remove()
Implemented LPOPPUSH (Class: PredisCommandsListPopPush)
Added tests for LPOPPUSH.
Renamed LPOPPUSH to RPOPLPUSH
Improved the parser for responses to INFO commands
Added a new assertion for ZSCORE. This assertion will fail if tests are run against a Redis instance built before Git commit 96d8b4e.
Fixed the tests for RPOPLPUSH as they were still using the old alias even after the command has been renamed from LPOPPUSH
Added more tests for RPOPLPUSH
Merge branch 'cmd_lpoppush'
Implemented ZINCRBY (Class: PredisCommandsZSetIncrementBy)
Renamed the class ListPushTailPopFirst into ListPopLastPushHead (did the same for it registered alias), the former name was incorrect
Fixed a bug when reading large bulk replies from remote Redis instances
Pipelines can now be initialized and used even without an anonymous function block. This is also needed to get pipelining support backported to PHP 5.2.
Refactored out in a new method of ConnectionParameters the code to get the value of a parameter or a default value if the same parameter is not set. This also fixes a few PHP notice messages.
Fix for a possible notice message thrown by PHP when there is no query string in the URI used to create a ConnectionParameters instance.
Made the constructor method of PredisClient more flexible with the passed arguments.
Reworked a bit the internals of PredisClient::create().
Removed leftovers from the old pipeline implementation.
Merge branch 'parameters'
Merge branch 'pipeline'Conflicts:ntlib/Predis.phpn

Added the new abstract class 'RedisServerCompatibility'. Its subclassess will be used to define a set compatibility profiles for each version of the Redis server. The only drawback is that the selected compatibility profile will be shared among multiple connections when using client-side sharding.
Added compatibility profiles for Redis server versions 1.0 and the upcoming 1.2.
PredisClient now uses the new compatibility profiles, though it is still hardcoded which profile to load.

Fixed a small bug in which the short alias for PredisCommandsDecrement was wrongly set to 'incr' instead of 'decr' (thanks to Jeff lewwid{at}gmail.com for noticing). The test suite is flawed in this respect since it uses only the extended aliases for commands but the short ones are not checked for correctness.
Same fix as commit 755c252 in master for the short alias of PredisCommandsDecrement
ConnectionCluster now implements the IteratorAggregate interface, thus enabling iterations over the registered connections simply by using a foreach loop.
The private method computeHash of ConnectionCluster is now a static method.
Slightly improved the internals of Command::getArgument and Command::getArguments.
The second parameter  for Client::createCommandInstance is now optional.
Refactored Client::executeCommand and introduced the new method Client::executeCommandOnShards which is useful to execute commands on all the connections registered in a ConnectionCluster instance.
When using a ConnectionCluster (sharding data over multiple servers), disallow sending commands that cannot be hashed by a key argument.
Client::executeCommandInternal must accept IConnection types! Stupid bugs are indeed stupid.
Moved the hash calculation for a command from ConnectionCluster to the command instance itself.
Removed the rather superfluous private method ConnectionCluster::getConnectionFromRing.
Trivial changes in HashRing::getNodeKey.
More trivial changes for HashRing::add and HashRing::remove.
Just removed a bunch of unuseful comments...
Renamed class RedisServerCompatibility to RedisServerProfile.
Added the new public method Client::setServerProfile.
Moved the default server profile class name to a private static variable of the Client class.
The second parameter for RedisServerProfile::createCommandInstance is now optional.
Added support for key tags: instead of hashing the full key, we hash only the portion enclosed within curly brackets.
Fixed the return value of PredisCommandsZSetIncrementBy as it does not return a boolean value but the current score after the increment operation.
Added tests for PredisCommandsZSetIncrementBy (ZINCRBY).
Merge branch 'cmd_zincrby'
Implemented the WITHSCORES option for ZRANGE and ZREVRANGE.
Extended the tests for ZRANGE and ZREVRANGE to cover the newly added WITHSCORES option.
Complete rewrite of the client construction and initialization bits.
Type checking + minor fixes +  more readable code for PredisClient::__construct and PredisClient::create.
Updated the test suite to work with the new parameters for PredisClient.
Updated the README with the new parameters for PredisClient. The old signature PredisClient(, ) is now completely deprecated and it does not work anymore.
Merge branch 'server_compat'Conflicts:ntlib/Predis.phpn
Updated TODO.

Changed the returned string used to hash a Connection instance when using a cluster of connections. IMPORTANT NOTE: if you are using a version of Predis older than this commit, then this change will surely have an impact on your existing partitioned data as it changes the distribution of server nodes over the ring.
Fix for a warning emitted by PHP when passing an array of strings parameters to PredisClient::create.
Removed a wrong type-check in PredisClient::setupConnection that was breaking the initialization of a cluster of connections when using an array of URI strings as parameters.
Changed the name of PredisClient::createCommandInstance into PredisClient::createCommand.
ZSetReverseRange now inherits from ZSetRange as the two commands share the same behaviour. This change allowed us to remove some code duplication.
Fixed E_STRICT notices that were being raised by PHP due to a slightly different method signature used for two command classes.
Removed a superfluous method call.
Fixed another E_STRICT notice that was being raised when using a pipeline.
Started hacking a bit on the new MULTI and EXEC commands.
Do not parse the response to a command if we get a QUEUED status reply from the server.
Implemented the new PredisMultiExecBlock class to wrap commands issued inside of MULTI + EXEC.
New PredisClient::multiExec method added.
Bugfix: return an empty string instead of null when the data length of a bulk reply is 0.
Added BLPOP and BRPOP.
Added connection_timeout and read_write_timeout as optional arguments for the ConnectionParameters class.
Implemented the __isset magic method for the ConnectionParameters class (it is useful to check if a parameter has been set).

Removed the default value for the read_write_timeout when initializing the connection stream. Now the timeout for r/w operations on the stream is set only if it has been set in the ConnectionParameters instance, otherwise the system default will be implicitly used (the default is usually 60 seconds).
Introduced a first draft of a new way to internally check for responses to enqueued commands.
Implemented RedisServerProfile::supportsCommand.
Bugfix: ListPopFirstBlocking is actually BLPOP, not BRPOP. This is what happens when you write code while thinking about something else...
Force the test suite to load the server profile for Redis edge versions (development unstable).
Added tests for MULTI / EXEC.
Merge branch 'multi_exec'
Commands issued with a MultiExecBlock now return ResponseQueued instances to the caller.
Throw a more meaningful exception if the server does not respond with a +QUEUED status reply to commands issued in a MULTI / EXEC context.
Switch to string-based versions for RedisServerProfile classes.
Renamed PredisClient::setServerProfile to PredisClient::setProfile.
Implemented PredisClient::getProfile.

Removed PredisClient::registerCommand and PredisClient::registerCommands as they are rarely used. The methods of the same name available in RedisServerProfile (and its derivates) serve the same purpose, use them from now on.
Reverted a bad versioning idea. The PredisRedisServer__Futures class will always be availabe and it represents the current development branch of Redis.
Casting a instance of PredisRedisServerProfile to string returns its associated version string.
Implemented PredisRedisServerProfile::compareWith, usefult to compare two different profiles. Its current behavior is the very same as PHP's version_compare.
Removed a bunch of unmeaningful TODOs end notes.
Use the new ternary short cut ?: where it helps with readability.
PredisCommandPipeline::execute and PredisMultiExecBlock::execute are no more limited to accepting only instances of Closure, now every kind of callable object can be passed as argument.
Fixed E_NOTICE messages in PredisRedisServerProfile::createCommand on undefined commands.
Fixed E_NOTICE messages in PredisResponse::getPrefixHandler on undefined handlers (unknown prefixes received from the server).
Added tests for BLPOP and BRPOP. They are not really that great as they are missing a concurrent RPUSHing client, but they are enough for now.
Merge branch 'blpop'Conflicts:ntlib/Predis.phpn
Reduced memory consumption for pipelines
Greatly improved the code that initially handles replies getting the correct reply handler. Also, performances might have improved a bit.
Improved the internals of MultiExecBlock::execute (slight reduction in memory usage; check for out-of-sync conditions between the client and the server)
Implemented Response::read. This new method groups Response::getPrefix and Response::getHeader (and reduces the overhead of unnecessary method calls).
Bumping year in the LICENSE file.
Updated the README.
Added checks for errors returned by read and write operations on sockets.
Using isset to check if prefix handlers have been initialized is faster.
Adjusted PredisCommandsBackgroundSave according to the new behavior of BGSAVE in Redis 1.2.
Minor changes in code formatting.
Changed the naming convention of the predefined RedisServerProfile derived classes.

The command ListPopLastPushHead (RPOPLPUSH) is now defined as an inline command instead of bulk after a change in Redis 1.2.1. The old bulk RPOPLPUSH has been preserved and renamed in ListPopLastPushHeadBulk, so that you can override the current server profile if you need the old (and uncorrect) behaviour when connecting to a Redis 1.2.0 instance.
Added the CHANGELOG file.
Added missing support for BGREWRITEAOF for Redis >= 1.2.0
Added tests for BGREWRITEAOF.
Implemented a factory method for creating server profiles instances.
Updated CHANGELOG
Fixed a dangerous oversight in the test suite (seriously, testing FLUSHALL was indeed stupid).
Enhancement: support multiple GET parameters for the SORT command (see also my comment in ISSUE #1)
Added missing test for SORT ... GET
Miss typings, oh my...
Switched from anonymous functions to classes extending the IResponseHandler interface to handle server responses.
Updated CHANGELOG
Implemented the new PredisUtilitiesMultiBulkResponseIterator.
MultiBulkResponseIterator::current must be pre-fetched.
MultiBulkResponseIterator now implements the Countable interface.
Ensure that iterators returned by multi-bulk replies inside a pipeline are stored in the replies buffer as arrays.
PredisClient::multiExec is now aware of iterable multi-bulk responses.

Users can now choose at runtime how to handle multibulk responses. The new (and optional) iterator-based approach is slightly slower than the usual fetch-all behaviour, but in certain scenarios (e.g. when dealing with massive multibulk responses) it can save a lot of memory on the client.
Enhancement: allows method chaining with commands pipelines.
Bugfix: the pipeline command buffer is not correctly reinitialized after CommandPipeline->flushPipeline.
Enhancement: allows method chaining with multi-exec blocks.
Updated CHANGELOG.
Use instanceof instead of the deprecated is_a().
Increased the default connection timeout from 2 to 5 seconds and moved the initialization of its value in ConnectionParameters->filterConnectionParams.
Enhancement: connections can now be identified by an alias (useful when connected to a cluster of Redis servers).
Updated CHANGELOG.
New command: APPEND (Redis v2.0-dev).
New command: ZCOUNT (Redis v2.0-dev).
Enhancement: ZRANGEBYSCORE now handles the WITHSCORES (Redis v2.0-dev) just like ZRANGE and ZREVRANGE.
Added test for ZRANGEBYSCORE with the WITHSCORES parameter.
Added tests for ZCOUNT.
Added tests for APPEND.
Implemented MultiBulkResponseKVIterator to wrap iterators that should be seen as $k => array($MBIterator, $MBIterator++) by external code (think of ZRANGE .. WITHSCORES as a practical example).
Enhancement: when using multibulk response iterators, ZRANGE and ZSETRANGE now return a MultiBulkResponseKVIterator when called with the WITHSCORES parameter.
MultiBulkResponseIterator and MultiBulkResponseKVIterator inherit from a common MultiBulkResponseIteratorBase class.
Non-static response reader
Private utility method ResponseReader->setHandler.
PredisCommandsKeys has been adjusted to handle the change in its reply type in a backwards-compatible way (the KEYS command will return a multibulk reply starting from Redis 2.0).
New command: DISCARD (Redis v2.0-dev).
Enhancement: added support for DISCARD in a MULTI / EXEC context initialized inside of an instance of MultiExecBlock.
Updated CHANGELOG.
Minor code rearrangements.
New command: SUBSTR (Redis v2.0-dev).
New command: ZRANK (Redis v2.0-dev).
Renamed PredisCommandsZCount to PredisCommandsZSetCount for naming consistency.
Updated CHANGELOG.
Minor code rearrangements.
Added tests for SUBSTR.
Added a test for SUBSTR on integer-encoded values.
Added tests for ZRANK.
Added tests for DISCARD.
New commands: HSET and HGET (Redis v2.0-dev). NOTE: this is the beginning of the Hashes awesomeness in Redis!
Fixed a small oversight.
Fixed tests against the current Redis master branch.
Get the current ResponseReader associated to a Client instance.
Enhanchement: added the ability to set options on a ResponseReader instance.
Get the current ResponseReader associated to a Connection instance.
Reverting some obsoleted changes in preparation for a merge into the master branch.
Merge branch 'response_reader' into integration
Merge branch 'multibulk_streaming_new'Conflicts:ntlib/Predis.phpn
Fixed internal API divergences between the two merged branches.
Enhancement: set how to handle multibulk replies (fetch the whole reply or stream it down to the user code).
Enhancement: set how to handle errors returned by the server (throw a ServerException or return a ResponseError instance that holds the error message).
Updated CHANGELOG.
New command: ZREVRANK (Redis v2.0-dev).
New command: ZREMRANGEBYRANK (Redis v2.0-dev).
New command: ZUNION (Redis v2.0-dev).
New command: ZINTER (Redis v2.0-dev).
Updated TODO.
Updated CHANGELOG.
Get ResponseReader options values.
Constants defined for Redis reply types in ResponseReader.
Allow a null parameters argument for the ConnectionParameters constructor (set to default).
New set of tests for client-specific features.
Tests for PredisConnectionParameters.
Tests for PredisRedisServerProfile.
Tests for PredisResponseQueued.
Tests for PredisResponseError.
Tests for PredisCommand.
Tests for PredisConnection.
Tests for PredisResponseReader.
Minor adjustments in a few tests.
Tests for PredisCommandPipeline.
// TODO stuff.
Bugfix: the response parser for KEYS raises a E_WARNING when using iterators for multi bulk responses against Redis v2.0.
Instead of passing around the actual socket resource, pass the Connection instance as argument.
Do not parse ResponseError instances.
Renamed PredisCommandsHSet and PredisCommandsHGet to PredisCommandsHashSet and PredisCommandsHashGet for naming consistency.
New command: HDEL (Redis v2.0-dev).
New command: HKEYS (Redis v2.0-dev).
New command: HVALS (Redis v2.0-dev).
New command: HGETALL (Redis v2.0-dev).
New command: HLEN (Redis v2.0-dev).
Wrong parameters passed to ClientException on write errors over the network.
Updated CHANGELOG.
Fixed failing tests due to changes introduced in Redis commits 3ea27d3, cc3b01c and 653c924.
New command: CONFIG (Redis v2.0-dev).
New command: HEXISTS (Redis v2.0-dev).
New command: HINCRBY (Redis v2.0-dev).
Updated CHANGELOG.
executeCommand is now part of the IConnection interface; Moved the actual implementation of executeCommand() from PredisClient to PredisConnection.
Added wrapping around for the consistent hashing algorithm.
Reworked HashRing::remove to handle hash collisions in a consistent way.
Made ConnectionCluster::getConnection public, so client code can check to which server a command would be sent.
Add support for microsecond read/write timeouts.
Added support for optionally weighted nodes in the hashring.
Added support for weight parameter in server configuration, that allows to balance the keys asymmetrically across multiple servers.
PredisClient::setProfile now accepts also a string value to specify the target server profile.
Added support for partial reads/writes. Note that stream_get_contents is not used because it doesn't seem to respect the timeout.
Bugfix: close the connection on Connection::rawCommand when the  parameter is set to TRUE.
Added support for async connections.
Removed a couple of redundant destructors.
New exceptions hierarchy.
Reworked the CommunicationException class and its derivates; When specified, close the underlying connection after a CommunicationException has been trown.
Disallow length parameter <= 0 for Connection::readBytes.
Changed the parameters order for the constructor of the PredisCommunicationException class.
Removed code duplication.
Introduced the new IRing interface.
Small refactoring of the HashRing class.
Introduced the new KetamaPureRing class with the same key distribution algorithm of libketama.
PredisConnectionCluster now accepts an instance of PredisUtilitiesIRing as an optional parameter.
Bugfix: wrap-around differences for HashRing and KetamaPureRing.
Precalculate the total count of the keys in the ring.
Added support for persistent connections (optional and experimental).
Close the underlying connection also on MalformedServerResponse exceptions.
Updated CHANGELOG.
Slightly changed the arguments order of HashRing::addNodeToRing.
Bugfix: missing backslash for root namespace.
Removed a spurious space character.
Implemented the new PredisClientOptions class.
PredisClient now uses the new PredisClientOptions class to define various options for a client instance.
Exposed ResponseReader::setHandler as a public method and implemented ResponseReader::getHandler.
Removed the setOption and getOption methods from ResponseReader as their implementation was clumsy.
Merge branch 'hashring_rework' into hyves_contribs_port
Merge branch 'client_options' into hyves_contribs_port
User-configurable key distribution algorithm to be used for clustered connections.
Updated CHANGELOG.
Removed a spurious new line.
Fixed the test suite to comply with the changes introduced in Redis with commit 4e27f26.
Fixed a bug in the test suite discovered thanks to the validation of numeric inputs introduced in Redis with commit bbe025e.
Get a PredisResponseError instance from a PredisServerException instance.
Added Lorenzo to the contributors list.
Updated README.
Updated CHANGELOG.
Updated CHANGELOG.
Merge branch 'hyves_contribs_port' into master. Huge thanks to Lorenzo Castelli for a lot of awesome improvements and ideas.
Merge branch 'test_client_feats' into test_library_features
Updated the tests to reflect the changes that has been made in the internal design of the library in the latest weeks.
Fixed a bug in the registration of the RPOPLPUSH command.
Converted the test suite to invoke commands on the client instance as they are defined in the command reference of Redis instead of using their aliases.
Re-enabled the test for SORT in the test suite.
Some performance improvements in the serialization of multibulk commands.
No more implicit serialization for an array instance passed as the single argument of a MultiBulkCommand.
Changed the way arguments of SLAVEOF are prepared before serialization to be compatible with an eventual switch to multi-bulk requests.
Changed the way arguments of SORT are prepared before serialization to be compatible with an eventual switch to multi-bulk requests.
Users can now register their own PredisRedisServerProfile class with one or more aliases.
Drop default support for Redis 1.0 and switch to the multi-bulk type for all of the Redis commands.
Providing optional support for Redis 1.0.
Updated CHANGELOG.
Moved the initialization of the default PredisResponseReader instance.
Renamed the PredisUtilitiesIRing interface to PredisUtilitiesIDistributionAlgorithm.
Moved the IDistributionAlgorithm interface one level up in the namespace chain, from PredisUtilities to Predis.
New PredisProtocol class. It's not really used right now...
Reminder for ZUNION.
New commands: PUBLISH, SUBSCRIBE and UNSUBSCRIBE (Redis v2.0-dev).
New command: HMSET (Redis v2.0-dev).

Slight code reorganization.
Updating comments.

Fix a couple of command aliases in the DEV profile.
Better support for options for ZUNION and ZINTER.
Test suite: updated tests for ZUNION and ZINTER with the new options style.
Updated TODO.
Bugfix: replies to DEL commands must not be converted to a boolean response as DEL returns the number of keys removed.
Trying to increment a string value associated to an hash now raises an error.
New commands: PSUBSCRIBE and PUNSUBSCRIBE (Redis v2.0-dev).
Implemented the new PredisPubSubContext class.
Added an example to show how to use the PredisPubSubContext class.
Updated TODO.

Merge branch 'test_library_features'
ZUNION and ZINTER have been changed to ZUNIONSTORE and ZINTERSTORE for consistency (see Redis commit 5d373da).
The default server profile for PredisClient is now 2.0 (supports for Redis v2.0 out of the box).
Handling of partial failures and server errors in pipelines.
Updated CHANGELOG.
Garbage in the LICENSE file. Seriously, what was that?
Bugfix: using the right variable in PredisPipelineSafeExecutor makes things work.
Test suite: minor code formatting changes.
Test suite: PredisClientFeaturesTestSuite and same signature of PHPUnit_Framework_TestCase::onNotSuccessfulTest.

Test suite: add test for the HASH type.

Throw a more appropriate InvalidArgumentException when a non-callable argument is passed to instances of PredisCommandPipeline and PredisMultiExecBlock.

Rename the PredisUtilities namespace to PredisShared.
Fix wrong namespace path for EmptyRingException.
Remove unused variable in the pubsub example.
Add the PredisClient::pubSubContext() method to initialize a PubSub context from a client instance.

Force disconnection in PredisPipelineStandardExecutor when a PredisServerException is thrown to prevent protocol desynchronization between the client and the server.

Fix an old but harmless glitch in the serialization of inline commands with 0 arguments.

Fast fail on exceptions different than PredisServerException or PredisCommunicationException.

First stub of the PredisCompatibility class. Things will most probably change later.
Code formatting.

Fix a bug in PredisNetworkStreamConnection::writeBytes().When PHP's fwrite() ends up writing only a part of $buffer over the network,nthis method attempts to automatically write the rest of $buffer. Due to thisnbug, the data being already sent to the server was not discarded from $buffer.nUsually fwrite() writes the whole $buffer in one go, but anyway this bug wouldnnot have passed unnoticed since it results in malformed requests and Redisnwould have surely returned a -ERR reply.n

[tests] Rewrite the whole test suite to allow more granular testing.Fix also a few bugs found while rewriting the test suite.nnIn order to be able to run integration tests, the test suite requiresna version of Redis >= 2.4.0.nnThe units have been splitted into several different groups usingnPHPUnit @group annotation to allow developers to enable, disablenand combine certain types of tests. The available groups are:nn  - disconnected: can run without a Redis server onlinen  - connected: active connection to a Redis server is requiredn  - commands: test dedicated to a specific Redis commandn  - slow: performs operations that can slow down execution;nnA list of the available groups can be obtained by runningnn  phpunit --list-groupsnnGroups of tests can be disabled or enabled via the XML configurationnfile or the standard command-line test runner. Please note that duento a bug in PHPUnit, older versions ignore the --group option whennthe group is excluded in the XML configuration file. Please refer tonhttp://github.com/sebastianbergmann/phpunit/issues/320 for detailsnnIntegration tests in the @connected group check if the command beingntested is defined in the selected server profile (see the value ofnthe TEST_SERVER_VERSION constant in phpunit.xml). If the command isnnot defined in the target server profile, the integration test isnautomatically marked as skipped.nnWe also provide an helper script in the bin directory that can benused to automatically generate a file with the scheleton of a testncase for a Redis command by specifying the name of the class in thenPredisCommands namespace. For example, to generate a test case fornSET (represented by the PredisCommandsStringSet class):nn  ./bin/generate-command-test.php --class=StringSetnnThe realm of a command is automatically inferred from the name of thenclass, but it can be set using the --realm option.n

Implement support for master / slave replication configurations.We used a new kind of virtual connection that, just like with cluster, groupsnmultiple connection objects and handles the logic needed to switch among themndepending on the kind of operation performed by commands..nnOur default implementation starts by picking up a random slave and switches tonthe master as soon as a command performing a write operation against a key isndetected. The master server will then be used for all the subsequent requestsnunless a manual switch to a different connection object is performed.nnRedis transactions are always performed on the master server, which means thatnthe switch to master is done as soon as the client issues a WATCH, MULTI ornany other command related to transactions.nnSee also https://github.com/nrk/predis/issues/21 for more details.n

Add new replication client option for master / slave replication.When the replication option is specified and evaluates to true, the array ofnconnection parameters passed to the client constructor os be used to initializena new instance of PredisNetworkIConnectionReplication. This option can alsonaccept a callable object used as an initializer or the fully-qualified name ofna class.n
Fix wrong usage of single-quotes for a string expecting interpolation.

Add the ability to mark specific commands or scripts for EVAL as read-only.As suggested by @Seldaek in ISSUE #21, it would be desiderable to have thenability to mark certain scripts for EVAL (and EVALSHA) as read-only to avoidnswitching to the master server when this is not really needed.nnWhen marking a script as read-only, only its SHA1 hash is saved to use lessnmemory and to make this work transparently for both EVAL and EVALSHA.n

Use Onion to build PEAR packages of Predis.Since Pearhub is currently broken (unfortunately the project does not seem tonbe actively mantained anymore) but we still want to have PEAR packages for ournlibrary, we need to automate the creation of a package.xml definition file tonbuild the actual packages that will be uploaded on a self-hosted PEAR channel.nnOnion, while still in its alpha stage right now, works perfectly fine for ournneeds and its own package.ini file looks simple enough to edit and maintain.nnSee http://c9s.github.com/Onion for more details about Onion and thank @c9snfor making it available.n
Use our own channel to distribute Predis via PEAR instead of PearHub.The new PEAR channel is self-hosted using Pirum.n

Add the ability to get a connection by alias from aggregated connections.Previously it was possible to create a new instance of PredisClient usingnthe alias of a single connection in a cluster of connections. Now we addednthe ability to do this also when using master/slave replication.n

Disallow certain commands when in replication mode.Some of these commands do not actually pose any threat, but their replies cannbe misleading since users do not know on which server they are connected to.nWe prefer to make things explicit so users can get a new client object out ofna specific connection in the replication pool to issue these commands.n

Make the profile option accept a callable object as initializer.This can be useful to set up the profile with additional commands,ne.g. when injecting new virtual commands based upon the EVAL andnthe PredisCommandsScriptedCommand class.n

Slightly optimize internals of MULTI / EXEC transactions.We start using SplQueue to enqueue the commands executed inside a MULTI /nEXEC context so that we can dequeue them for parsing their replies later.nnThis change does not affect performances but makes the code more clean.n

Add a pipeline executor that internally uses MULTI / EXEC.The actual pipeline is wrapped between MULTI and EXEC to ensure that all thencommands are correctly sent and executed on the server. Use specific command hash strategy for redis-cluster.This is needed because redis-cluster does not support the same commandsnor operations that can be performed with our client-side managed predisncluster.nnFor example redis-cluster does not support key tagging (that is, partsnof a key enclosed by {...} to hash only that specific part of a key)nand multiple-key operations suchs as MGET, MSET, SDIFF, SUNION or SINTER.nSome multiple-key operations can be performed anyway if the command hasnonly one key (e.g. MGET foo and MSET foo bar will not fail).n

Make it possible to pre-associate slots to a connection.This is useful to avoid guessing the correct server instance at runtimenthus reducing the overhead of a guess-and-try approach since relying onn-ASK or -MOVED responses returned by a node is a costly operation.nnFor now, you can pre-associate slots using the cluster client option:nn$parameters = array(n'tcp://127.0.0.1:6379',n'tcp://127.0.0.1:6380',n'tcp://127.0.0.1:6381',n);nn$options = array(n'cluster' => function ($options) {n$cluster = new PredisConnectionRedisCluster();nn$cluster->setSlots(0,1364, '127.0.0.1:6379');n$cluster->setSlots(1365, 2729, '127.0.0.1:6380');n$cluster->setSlots(2730, 4095, '127.0.0.1:6381');nnreturn $cluster;n},n);nn$client = new PredisClient($parameters, $options);nnIn the future we will make the slots configuration easier by fetchingnthe configuration from a node using the command CLUSTER NODES or bynpre-computing the slices of slots associated to a node when adding itnto the cluster connection object.n

Pre-associate connections to slot ranges using connection parameters.This makes it possible to easily assign a connection to a slot rangenusing the key slots in connection parameters like in the followingnexample:nn$parameters = array(n'tcp://127.0.0.1:6379?slots=0-1364',n'tcp://127.0.0.1:6380?slots=1365-2729',n'tcp://127.0.0.1:6381?slots=2730-4095',n);nn$options = array('cluster' => 'redis');n$client = new PredisClient($parameters, $options);nnIt is possible to get the full list of slot ranges for each node ofnthe cluster using redis-cli connected to one of the nodes:nn./redis-cli -h 127.0.0.1 -p 6379 CLUSTER NODESnnThe last column in the resulting output contains the slots assignednto each instance participating to the redis cluster.n
Optimize lazy initialization of the slots map.This is twice faster than before but still kind of slow compared to theninitialization of a cluster with no slots pre-assigned to connections.n
Remove useless use directives.
Improve the slot-guessing algorithm.This change makes it almost useless to pre-assign slots using connectionnparameters, but the functionality will be kept for special cases.n

Move the hash generator inside the command hash strategy class.This should make things a tiny bit faster (we are speaking about micronoptimizations anyway) but more  importantly it results in a betternencapsulation.n
Fix and optimize node guessing algorithm.

Support EVAL and EVALSHA with client-side sharding (Predis cluster).We extract the keys from commands using the second argument of EVAL /nEVALSHA which specifies the number of arguments that must be treatednas keys (used to populate the KEYS table in the Lua script) and thennwe check if all the keys generate the same hash using the usual method.nnOur scripted command abstraction is also supported.nnIt comes without saying that accessing or setting keys from within thenLua script is something that might not work as expected, so you shouldnbe careful when using EVAL and EVALSHA in the context of client-sidensharding.n

Support EVAL and EVALSHA with redis-cluster.We extract the keys from commands using the second argument of EVAL /nEVALSHA which specifies the number of arguments that must be treatednas keys (used to populate the KEYS table in the Lua script) and thennwe check if there is only one key since redis-cluster right now doesnnot support multi-keys requests.nnOur scripted command abstraction is also supported.n

Implement PHP iterator based on the SCAN command (Redis 2.8).This iterator allows to perform full iterations over the keyspace of a Redisninstance by wrapping the incremental nature of SCAN using an abstraction thatnfits perfectly in userland code:nn  $client = new PredisClient('tcp://127.0.0.1', ['profile' => '2.8']);n  $iterator = new PredisIteratorScanKeyspaceIterator($client);nn  foreach ($iterator as $key) {n  echo $key . PHP_EOL;n  }nnMemory consumption during an iteration is limited because elements are fetchednincrementally, on the other hand SCAN gives limited guarantees about returnednelements since the underlying collection (the keyspace in this case) can changenduring the whole iteration process. The most immediate drawback is that the samenelement may be returned multiple times.nnSee http://redis.io/commands/scan to fully understand the inner workings,nand particularly the Scan guarantees paragraph.n

Extract base class for iterators based on the SCAN family of commands.The iterators based on SCAN, SSCAN, ZSCAN and HSCAN will extend this abstractnclass to share most of the logic which is common for all of the Redis commandsnin the SCAN family.n

Implement PHP iterator based on the SSCAN command (Redis 2.8).This iterator allows to perform full iterations over the members of a setnby wrapping the incremental nature of SSCAN just like we did for SCAN:nn  $client = new PredisClient('tcp://127.0.0.1', ['profile' => '2.8']);n  $iterator = new PredisIteratorScanSetIterator($client, set_key);nn  foreach ($iterator as $member) {n  echo $member . PHP_EOL;n  }nnBeing SSCAN closely related to SCAN, it is subject to the same behaviour,nsee http://redis.io/commands/scan for reference.nnMehn

Implement PHP iterator based on the ZSCAN command (Redis 2.8).This iterator allows to perform full iterations over the members of a sortednset by wrapping the incremental nature of ZSCAN just like we did for SCAN:nn  $client = new PredisClient('tcp://127.0.0.1', ['profile' => '2.8']);n  $iterator = new PredisIteratorScanSortedSetIterator($client, zset_key);nn  foreach ($iterator as $member => $rank) {n  echo $rank => $member . PHP_EOL;n  }nnBeing ZSCAN closely related to SCAN, it is subject to the same behaviour,nsee http://redis.io/commands/scan for reference.nnThis iterator implementation returns the member as key and the rank as valuensince the rank is a float value which would be truncated when transformingnthe iteration to an array (e.g. using iterator_to_array()). Luckily PHPnpreserves the insertion order for named arrays members still result sorted.n

Implement PHP iterator based on the HSCAN command (Redis 2.8).This iterator allows to perform full iterations over fields and values of anhash by wrapping the incremental nature of HSCAN just like we did for SCAN:nn  $client = new PredisClient('tcp://127.0.0.1', ['profile' => '2.8']);n  $iterator = new PredisIteratorScanHashIterator($client, hash_key);nn  foreach ($iterator as $field => $value) {n  echo $field => $value . PHP_EOL;n  }nnBeing HSCAN closely related to SCAN, it is subject to the same behaviour,nsee http://redis.io/commands/scan for reference.n

Rename for the last time all the iterator classes.We are experimenting with a new approach at naming classes using lessnredundant names by leveraging the containing namespace. The PHP usendirective is not limited to class names but can be used to import thenwhole namespace, which means you can do something like this:nn  use PredisCollectionIterator;n  // ...n  foreach (new IteratorKeyspace($client) as $key) {n  t// ...n  }nnAlternatively you can always rely on use ... as ... to import one ofnthe classes by giving it a more meaningful name in the context of thenroot namespace:nn  use PredisCollectionIteratorKeyspace as KeyspaceIterator;n  // ...n  foreach (new KeyspaceIterator($client) as $key) {n  t// ...n  }nnIn this specific case we chose to apply the -Key postfix to classesniterating Redis keys to be more explicit about the fact that thoseniterators does not work on local in-memory collections, but fetchnitems from a key stored on a remote Redis server.n

Diverging from the v0.8 branch (current stable).This commit marks the start of works for the next major release ofnPredis which will bring various breaking changes needed to polish theninternal design making the library even more flexible to use or extendnand, more importantly, almost stable in terms of API.nnThe Redis commands API exposed by PredisClient is not going to changenmuch if not at all which is a good news. The most immediate changesnaffecting developers will involve the renaming of a few namespaces andnclasses, the removal of some previously deprecated classes and methodsnand some tweaks to the current abstractions.nnRight now the plan is to have a fast paced development to release thisnversion as soon as possible, ideally a few weeks later than Redis 2.8,nthen wait to see the final definition of redis-cluster so that we canntweak our code if needed and finally hit the v1.0.0 milestone with asnfew changes as possible. Furthermore, v1.x will most likely be thenlast version of Predis supporting PHP 5.3 as we will start migratingnto PHP 5.4 (or even 5.5) with v2.x, which is not going to happen soonnanyway.n

Reimplement from scratch client configuration.This commit is a complete rewrite of the classes previously containednin the PredisOption namespace aimed at lowering the initializationnoverhead while bringing in more consistency. The overall idea is stillnthe same with a mini DI container, PredisConfigurationOptions, whichncarries options with values that can be initialized lazily.nnThe first difference with our previous implementation is that now evennuser-defined options can be initialized lazily, everything needed isnan object responding to the __invoke() magic method such as a closure.nOther kind of callable arguments (strings, arrays) will be treated asnplain values. The only drawback is that we cannot pass any instance ofnclasses implementing __invoke() as an option value, but considered thenlimited scope of our use case we can say it's more of an acceptablencompromise. Callbacks used for lazy initialization will receive twonarguments upon invokation:nn  - The current instance of PredisConfigurationOption ($options)n  - A string containing the name of the option ($option)nnThis is an example in actual code:nn  $options = new PredisConfigurationOptions([n'exceptions' => true,n'profile' => '2.8',n'distributor' => function () {n  return new PredisClusterDistributionKetamaPureRing();n},n'cluster' => function ($options) {n  $distr= $options->distributor;n  $strategy = new PredisClusterPredisClusterHashStrategy($distr);n  $cluster  = new PredisConnectionPredisCluster();nn  return $cluster;n},n'connections' => function ($options, $option) {n  $factory = $options->getDefault($option);n  $factory->define('tcp', 'PredisConnectionPhpiredisConnection');nn  return $factory;n},n  ]);nnAs you can see there's very little difference compared to before innthe actual usage as most changes are under the hood. Some options suchnas exceptions and replication can now correctly parse bool valuesnfrom strings (so the string false is not evaluated as boolean true).nnWhile options were initially conceived to configure the client and itsnbehavior, the concept has matured and it's perfectly fine to considernthe use of PredisConfigurationOptions to propagate configurations toninner parts of the library.n

Add option aggregate to customize multiple connections aggregation.This option must return a callable object that is used to override hownthe client aggregates connections when passing an array of parametersnto its constructor.nnWhen specified, this option overrides both cluster and replicationnas it allows to make use of your own code to aggregate multiple nodes.nnThis is, for example, how you can mimic the standard initialization ofna cluster that relies on client-side sharding:nn  $parameters = ['tcp://127.0.0.1:6380', 'tcp://127.0.0.1:6381'];nn  $options = [n'aggregate' => function () {n  return function ($parameters, $options) {n  $connection = new PredisConnectionPredisCluster();n  $options->connections->aggregate($connection, $parameters);nn  return $connection;n  };n},n  ];nn  $client = new PredisClient($parameters, $options);nnWhen invoked by the client, the specified callable must always returnna PredisConnectionConnectionInterface instance or the client willnthrow an UnexpectedValueException.n

Add new command class useful to execute raw Redis commands.By raw we mean that input arguments are not filtered and responses arennot parsed, which means arguments must follow the command signature asndefined by Redis and complex responses are left untouched.nnWhen instantiating an instance of `PredisCommandRawCommand` you mustnpass at least the command ID. You can pass further arguments in thenarray or you can just set them later with `RawCommand::setArguments()`nbut you cannot modify the command ID once instantiated.nn  $command = new PredisCommandRawCommand(['SET', 'foo', 'bar']);n  $response = $client->executeCommand($command);nnWhile higher level abstractions built upon `PredisClient` should justnuse commands created by the profile in use, inner parts of the librarynmight use raw commands to provide certain functionalities making surenthat input and output of commands are always consistent, independentnof the profile.n

Add the ability for the client to send raw commands to Redis.When sending raw commands their arguments are not filtered, responsesnare not parsed and key prefixes are not applied. The client also doesnnot throw any exception on Redis errors regardless of its settings.nnThe first parameter takes the raw arguments of the command (includednits identifier) as defined by the Redis documentation while the secondnoptional parameter is always populated by reference to indicate whennRedis actually returned an error response.nn  $client->raw(['PING']);// PONGn  $client->raw(['SET','foo','bar']); // OKn  $client->raw(['GET','foo'], $err); // bar, $err=FALSEn  $client->raw(['LPUSH','foo',1], $err); // WRONGTYPE..., $err=TRUEnnInternally, this method creates instances of PredisCommandRawCommandnthat get passed to the underlying connection instance for execution asnif they were usual commands defined by Predis.nnRaw commands work in both cluster and replication scenarios since theynare recognized by their command ID, but key prefixing is not supportednsince it is done by the profile instance when instantiating commands.n

Use PredisResponseStatus to identify all kinds of status responses.Status response objects are needed mostly to make it possible from thenclient perspective to differentiate a status response with the payloadnOK from a normale bulk reply containing OK.nnThe biggest change is for commands returning +OK responses: these werenpreviously translated to TRUE (bool value), but they are now returnednas instances of PredisResponseStatus. Just to illustrate an examplenof the possibilities with this change we will use SET since it is thenmost widely used command returning +OK:nn  $response = $client->set('foo', 'bar');nn  echo $response; // 'OK'n  $response == 'OK';  // TRUEn  isset($response->ok);   // TRUEn  $response == true;  // TRUEn  $response === true; // FALSEn  $response instanceof PredisResponseObjectInterface; // TRUEn  $response instanceof PredisResponseStatus;  // TRUEnnFor those checking responses returned by commands such as SET or PONG,nthe breaking change basically lies in the usage of strict comparison:ndoing $response === true will now evaluate to FALSE instead of TRUE.nnBy default Predis caches common status responses such as OK or QUEUEDnto lower the memory usage when using pipelines or transactions.n

Redesign the whole internals for clustering.This change actually had a positive impact on the design of the wholeninternals for clustering which is now cleaner and easier to maintain.nIt is still far from perfect, but we also have to keep performances innconsideration so we can say that we ended up with a good compromise.nnPreviously Predis assigned an hash to each command instance which wasncomputed from its key, now we changed approach and the library cachesnthe slot assigned to each command. This works for both our client-sidensharding cluster and the upcoming redis-cluster, but the former is thenone that needed most changes.nnThe PredisCluster aggregate connection now only takes an instance ofnStrategyInterface, which in turn wraps the chosen distributor. Afternall, in order to be able to calculate the assigned slot for a commandnor key, the cluster strategy must have access to the distributor thatnmanages the distribution of the whole keyspace. Nothing really changesnin terms of configurability as it is still possible to decide whichndistributor to use for client-side sharding, it is simply different:nn  $distributor = new PredisClusterDistributionKetamaRing();n  $strategy = new PredisClusterPredisStrategy($distributor);n  $cluster = new PredisConnectionAggregatePredisCluster($strategy);nnAs for the RedisCluster aggregate connection, the only change is thatnthe mathematical operation of calculating the assigned slot from a keynhas been completely moved inside the cluster strategy instance.nnThe strategy for redis-cluster does not use external distributors sontrying to StrategyInterface::getDistributor() will throw an exception.nThis may change in future releases, but this is not a priority sincenredis-cluster relies on a fixed, well-defined distribution mechanism.n

Makes it easier to use a custom parameters class.Simply overriding one method of the standard connection factory class,nused internally by Predis, allows developers to use their own customnconnection parameters classes through the whole library.nnFor example, in order to support Heroku-style URIs one can do:nn  class HerokuParameters extends PredisConnectionParametersn  {nprotected function filter(array $parameters)n{n  if (nisset($parameters['scheme']) &&n$parameters['scheme'] === 'redis'n  ) {n$parameters['scheme'] = 'tcp';n  }nn  if (isset($parameters['pass'])) {n$parameters['password'] = $parameters['pass'];n  }nn  unset($parameters['user'], $parameters['pass']);nn  return $parameters;n}n  }nn  class ConnectionFactory extends PredisConnectionFactoryn  {nprotected function createParameters($parameters)n{n  return HerokuParameters::create($parameters);n}n  }nn  $client = new PredisClient($_ENV['REDISCLOUD_URL'], [n'connections' => new ConnectionFactory()n  ]);nnThis idea comes in response to #196, but since we do not want to bakensupport for SaaS-specific URIs in Predis this is the best compromisenwe can offer leave developers free to implement their own logic fornhandling these kind of URIs with the additional benefit of having itnavailable through the whole library (think of cluster or replicationnwhere you have multiple nodes, thus multiple instances of connectionnparameters to create).n

Use persistent with non-bool strings to open different persistent connections.stream_socket_client() has the undocumented ability to open different persistentnstreams by providing a path in the $address string. Previously we supported thisnbehaviour with a combination of persistent and path (see #139) but this cannbe confusing, especially now that we support the redis:// scheme which uses thenpath part of an URI string to specify a database number.nnAfter this change, instead of using an URI string such as:nn  $parameters = 'tcp://127.0.0.1/first?persistent=1&database=5';nnYou should use the following ones:nn  $parameters = 'tcp://127.0.0.1?persistent=first&database=5';n  $parameters = 'redis://127.0.0.1/5?persistent=first';nnAvoiding path makes even more sense when using array connection parameters:nn  $parameters = [n'host'   => '127.0.0.1',n'database'   => 5,n'persistent' => 'first',n  ]nnThis feature is not supported when using UNIX domain sockets because the pathntrick of stream_socket_client() does not play well with the actual path of thensocket file. The client will throw an InvalidArgumentException exception tonnotify the user.nnNOTE: unfortunately we have to disable the tests for persistent connections whennrunning under HHVM due to a bug in their implementation of get_resource_type()npreventing us to recognize a persistent stream from userland code.n

Add support for default connection parameters in ConnectionFactory.These parameters augment the set of user-supplied parameters when creating a newnconnection, but they do not override specific parameters when already defined.nnAn example of self-contained configuration using client options:nn  $client = new PredisClient('tcp://127.0.0.1', [n'parameters' => [n  'timeout' => 10,n],n'connections' => function ($options) {n  $factory = $options->getDefault('connections');n  $factory->setDefaultParameters($options->parameters);nn  return $factory;n},n  ]);nnThis change will be useful for both redis-cluster and redis-sentinel as it makesnit easy to apply shared parameters such as a common password for authenticationnwhen the server returns one ore more new nodes from response (think of -MOVED).n

Remove timeout as a default parameter in ConnectionParameters.Falling back to a default timeout values should be done by the connection classnas it is an implementation detail that may vary depending on the backend.n

Remove ConnectionAggregateRedisCluster::setDefaultParameters().The redis-cluster connection relies on a client-initialized connection factory,nso use ConnectionFactory::setDefaultParameters() to set the default parametersnthat must be applied to new nodes discovered through -MOVED or -ASK responses.n

Implement TLS/SSL-encrypted connections.This is handy for accessing remote Redis instances over a secure SSL connectionnwhich is currently a popular option or even requirement with many cloud hostingnenvironments.nnIn order to configure the client to use an SSL-encrypted connection the schemenin the connection parameters must be either tsl or rediss and a set of SSLnoptions (see http://php.net/manual/en/context.ssl.php) must be provided via thenssl parameter as a named array.nnThe following example (which does not necessarily represent an example of goodnpractices!) illustrates how to set the ssl parameter using a named array andnthe equivalent URI string:nn  // Parameters as named arrayn  $parameters = [n'scheme' => 'tls',n'host'   => '127.0.0.1',n'ssl'=> [n'cafile'=> '/home/adaniele/redis.pem',n'verify_peer_name'  => false,n],n  ];nn  // Parameters as URI stringn  $parameters = 'tls://127.0.0.1?ssl[cafile]=redis.pem&ssl[verify_peer_name]=1';nnSupport for SSL is currently limited to the PredisConnectionStreamConnectionnbackend but we intend to investigate if it is possible to extend this featurento PredisConnectionPhpiredisStreamConnection in the future.nnBe aware that using encrypted connections may lead to a performance degradationnespecially in the connect() operation due to the overhead of the TLS handshake.nUnfortunately there is no real way to reuse SSL sessions from userland, asidenfrom enabling persistent connections, but this will work only on PHP >= 7.0.0nbecause previous versions of PHP do not provide enough info about a stream fromnget_stream_meta_data().nnNOTE: Redis does not have built-in support for SSL-encrypted connections, but ifnyou want to expose it to public networks you may want to rely on stunnel.n

Change format required for URI strings when using unix scheme.Instead of using unix:// you should just use unix::nn  $old = 'unix:///path/to/redis.sock';n  $new = 'unix:/path/to/redis.sock';nnThe old format should be considered obsolete and will not be supportednstarting from the next major release of Predis.nMehn

Implement full support for IPv6.Using IPv6 with Predis was basically impossible due to various inconsistenciesnand bugs through the library, now it is supported by all the connection classes.nnFollowing the standard for IPv6 literal addresses in URI strings, the IP literalnmust be enclosed within square brackets when passing the parameters as a string:nn  $parameters = 'tcp://[2001:db8:0:f101::1]:6379';nnSee https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc3986#section-3.2.2 for further details.nnThis commit also fixes #239 making redis-cluster usable with nodes using IPv6.n

Fix severe regression on HHVM.Apparently HHVM is more strict than PHP in stream_socket_client() and does notnlike at all IPv4 addresses and hostnames eclosed in square brackets. Note thatnit is not that weird as square brackets are mandatory only when IPv6 addressesnare embedded in URI strings, so it is more like a weird incompatiblity of HHVMnwith the behaviour of the standard PHP interpreter. The connect() attempt failsnbut not due to the server being unavailable or some connectivity issue.nnThe important lesson is: never rely on undocumented behaviours especially whenntargeting different runtimes, and do not forget to run the test suite on everynplatform right before release like I unfortunately did.n

Add initial support for redis-sentinel.This is a first implementation that is based on the work of @vmattila but somenmore changes and missing bits are required in order to be considered complete.nnTo leverage redis-sentinel the client must be configured using the aggregatenoption instead of the usual replication option, thought this may change fornthe release of Predis v1.1.0 (it __will__ change for Predis v2.0.0 but this isna whole different matter). This is a configuration example:nn  use PredisConnectionAggregateSentinelReplication;nn  $sentinels = [n'tcp://127.0.0.1:5381',n'tcp://127.0.0.1:5382',n'tcp://127.0.0.1:5383',n  ];nn  $client = new PredisClient($sentinels, [n'service' => 'nrk-master',n'aggregate' => function() {n  return function ($sentinels, $options) {n$service = $option->service;n$connections = $options->connections;nnreturn new SentinelReplication($sentinels, $service, $connections);n  };n},n  ]);nnThe missing bits right now are:nn  - A more solid handling of failures when querying sentinels.n  - When the connection fails while executing a command on one of the servers,nwe should query again a sentinel and then re-issue the command accordingly.n

Specify a timeout for the connect() operation to sentinel servers.This value should be reasonably low so that the client can fallback to the nextnsentinel if the connect() operation is taking too much and slowing things down.nnWhen the connection parameters of sentinels contain a timeout parameter, itsnvalue takes the precedence over the default sentinels timeout.n

Implement transparent auto-retry of commands upon server failure.By default, when the current server dies while executing a command Predis asksnfor a new configuration to one of the sentinels and re-issues the same command.nnThis behavior can be disabled calling SentinelReplication::setAutomaticRetry().n

Implement ability to fetch an updated list of sentinels from active sentinel.This can be optionally done automatically but is disabled by default, just usenSentinelReplication::setUpdateSentinels() accordingly to enable the automaticnfetching of an updated list of sentinels.n

Implement discovery in basic replication.Now the client can discover the whole replication configuration bynasking to one of the servers (master has the precedence) using thenINFO REPLICATION command. Try again on connection failure to node in cluster.When the connection to a node in the cluster fails in the attempt tonexecute a command, Predis now removes the failed connection from thencluster pool and contacts a random node to ask for a fresh slots mapnand tries to execute the command once again.nnWhen the cluster is configured to have each master replicated to onenor more slaves, one the slaves is automatically promoted to the rolenof master by redis-cluster with this change being reflected in thenoutput of CLUSTER SLOTS, so the next execution should run just fine.nnOur current approach is relatively naive as CLUSTER SLOTS is executednagainst a random master node, meaning that the client must open a newnconnection and execute one more roundtrip only to fetch the new slotsnmap. For now it is enough, it is still better than having the clientnfail when you actually have somes slaves in your redis-cluster setup,nbut one improvement could consist in caching the list of slaves forneach master returned in the response of CLUSTER SLOTS so that when anconnection fails the client can try to guess which connection shouldnuse for the next attempt.nnThis commit closes #173, closes #215, and closes #314.n

Fix GC issues with closures for phpiredis reader handlers.The following code, despite not being something you would do in realnworld scenarios, eventually ended up generating an exception for Toonmany open files.nn  for ($i = 0; $i < 10000; $i++) {n$client = new PredisClient();n$client->connect();n  }nnThe reason was that the destructor for the connection was not invokednby PHP as expected when the client instance went out of scope, so thenunderlying stream resource were not being properly released.nEven without an actual connect() operation, the memory usage of PHPnkept growing until exhausting the configured value of max memory.nnThe source of the issue is related to the use of closures as handlersnfor the phpiredis reader resource, to be more precise it seems to bensome kind of circular reference memory leak. Apparently PHP does notnlike the fact that a closure, automatically bound to $this startingnwith PHP 5.4, is stored in the reader resource which in turn is keptnreferenced by $this. This ends up the refcount not going down thusnthe GC does not collect those connection objects going out of scope.nThis is confirmed by the fact that this issue is not triggered whennusing PHP 5.3 where the ZE does not automatically bind closures ton$this, unless you capture $this with the use() directive (andnthe usual $that = $this trick).nnUsing a static assignement instead of simply returning new closuresnin getStatusHandler() and getErrorHandler() is kind of an hacknthat seems to be working fine, the added value of this solution isnthat we do not have to break the internal API of the three connectionnbackends based on ext-phpiredis.nnThis commit fixes #345.n
